<HEADLINE>
<P>
EDUCATION SECRETARY CAVAZOS' CRITICISM OF LATINO PARENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The criticism of Latino parents by Cavazos was inaccurate, simplistic, crude 
and irresponsible. 
</P>
<P>
Students, teachers and parents are equally accountable for attaining 
educational goals. 
</P>
<P>
To single out the parental role as a primary cause of the 40% dropout rate 
among Latino students unfairly cast a perception of negligence upon the people 
most deserving of respect. 
</P>
<P>
The value of learning is a central theme to us. Assimilation requires a daily 
assessment of this value. The Hispanic-American family is not anti-education. 
We are striving to assert our presence within an educational system that is 
culturally biased toward Anglo-American values; individualism, rationalism, 
empiricism. 
</P>
<P>
Adopting English as a second language causes students to make decisions 
regarding attachment and loyalty. English speakers are the public role models 
in the classroom. Spanish-speaking parents are a private resource outside the 
cultural mainstream. Latino students are asked to bridge the language and 
cultural gaps between home and school. The high number of dropouts indicates 
the schools are losing this battle. 
</P>
<P>
Cavazos is alerting Latinos to a future of limited opportunity due to low 
educational advancement. To avert this plight parents are calling for 
courageous leadership and not petty backbiting from the nation's top education 
official. 
</P>
<P>
EDDY POLANCO 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
