<HEADLINE>
<P>
BULGARIAN COMMUNISTS ARE EXPECTED TO WIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SOFIA, Bulgaria 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Communists, with support from Bulgarians who favor a slower pace toward reform, 
are expected to clinch a strong parliamentary victory in runoff elections held 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
State television reported some voting irregularities, including illegal 
canvassing near polling stations. But the voting generally appeared to go 
smoothly. 
</P>
<P>
The 400-seat Parliament, the first freely elected legislature in Bulgaria in 58 
years, will have a substantial number of opposition lawmakers, and their 
presence will mark the end of rubber-stamp approval for policies of the former 
rulers. 
</P>
<P>
The Communists -- who now call themselves Socialists -- were the winners in the 
first round of voting on June 10, garnering 172 seats. They needed to win only 
29 of the 81 seats being decided in the runoffs to gain an absolute majority. 
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Alexander Lilov was a first-round winner, but Prime Minister 
Andrei Lukanov faced a runoff. 
</P>
<P>
The main opposition alliance, the United Democratic Forces, won 107 seats in 
the first round, and other opposition groups won 40. The alliance and the 
Agrarian Party, a once docile ally of the Communists, have both vowed not to 
join a coalition with the new Communists. 
</P>
<P>
However, Communist and United Democratic Forces officials have said they might 
form a government of specialists chosen on the basis of their expertise rather 
than their political affiliation. 
</P>
<P>
Polls opened at 7 a.m. and closed at 6 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
Dimiter Popov, secretary of the Central Electoral Commission, said the 
commission expects to announce the results Tuesday, the state news agency BTA 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
State television said 75% of the eligible voters had cast ballots shortly 
before the polls closed. In the first first round, 91% voted. 
</P>
<P>
First-round results show that in 22 of the 81 constituencies where balloting 
was repeated Sunday, Communist candidates had a substantial lead over their 
rivals, and in 33 others they had a slight edge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
