<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: 'MORNING AFTER' PILL WAS FOUND TO HOLD FUTURE RISKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, AND TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Q. I was married until last year and had been on birth control pills. After the 
divorce I didn't plan on needing any contraception for a long time so I stopped 
taking them. 
</P>
<P>
To my surprise I met someone recently I really like and got carried away one 
evening. I remembered that when I was in college the student health center 
provided a "morning-after" contraceptive for such situations. But my doctor 
didn't know what I was talking about when I called for a prescription. 
</P>
<P>
Luckily I didn't get pregnant, but I've been wondering what happened to the 
morning-after pill. 
</P>
<P>
A. Several decades ago DES (diethylstilbestrol) was used as a morning-after 
contraceptive. Unfortunately, it often caused nausea and vomiting in the high 
doses required. 
</P>
<P>
Worse, DES posed a long-term threat. Some young women exposed to DES before 
birth, when their mothers took it during pregnancy, develop a rare vaginal 
cancer. Once this danger of DES was discovered, most doctors stopped using it 
as a morning-after pill for fear that if it did not work and a daughter were 
born, she would be at risk. 
</P>
<P>
The Food and Drug Administration has not approved any medication for use as a 
morning-after contraceptive but some physicians prescribe the birth control 
pill Ovral for this purpose. According to the Medical Letter of Drugs and 
Therapeutics, in the appropriate dose this medication is usually effective 
against pregnancy if it is taken within one to three days after intercourse. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Your column once carried a letter from a man who used a prescription 
athlete's foot cream for his itchy and scaly scalp. I think the medicine 
started with the letter "N." I wanted to save the article and ask my doctor if 
he'd prescribe that cream for me to try. Unfortunately, I've misplaced it. What 
was that stuff? 
</P>
<P>
A. The medicine in question was Nizoral (ketoconazole), a prescription 
anti-fungal agent effective for a variety of skin conditions. The cream has 
been shown to work against the scaling and flaking of seborrheic dermatitis. 
People with severe dandruff may also benefit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061890-0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 235822 </DOCID>
